    <div class="wrap narrow">
      <h2>Beko in LA — compact European-spec dishwashers for urban kitchens</h2>
      <p>
        Beko occupies a specific niche in LA's dishwasher market that most mass-market brands don't
        target. Arçelik's 2007 US entry focused on European-spec built-in dishwashers — stainless-steel
        tubs as a baseline specification (not a premium upgrade), noise profiles in the 39-49 dB range,
        18-inch and 24-inch widths with heavy emphasis on the 18-inch compact that most US mass-market
        brands don't build. For LA, that specification set finds its natural home in urban compact
        kitchens: WeHo condo flips where the kitchen is small but the design aesthetic is tight, Koreatown
        apartment remodels where the cabinetry doesn't accommodate 24-inch, Silver Lake and Highland Park
        mid-century renovations that preserve original small-kitchen footprints, Downtown LA residential
        towers where unit sizes cap at 600-900 square feet, and the growing LA Airbnb + short-term rental
        segment where hosts spec compact dishwashers to maximize countertop and cabinet space.
      </p>
      <p>
        Our LA Beko service territory concentrates in exactly those geographies. Volume is strongest in
        the urban condo + apartment belt from WeHo through Koreatown, Hollywood, and Downtown LA, with
        secondary volume across Silver Lake, Echo Park, Highland Park, and Mount Washington (design-
        forward neighborhoods where Beko landed as the under-$1,000 European dishwasher option when
        Miele and Bosch 800 Series were out of budget). Third volume pocket: Westside guesthouse and
        ADU installs where 18-inch compact is the only option that fits the auxiliary-kitchen
        cabinetry. We keep Beko + Blomberg cross-platform parts in dispatch rotation — the two brands
        share chassis architecture on multiple service items, which accelerates first-visit repair.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section alt">
    <div class="wrap">
      <h2>Beko dishwasher failures our techs see most often in LA</h2>
      <p class="intro">
        Pattern data from our Beko service calls. Compact-chassis architecture produces a specific
        failure profile different from 24-inch standard dishwashers.
      </p>

      <div class="fail-block">
        <h3>Won't drain — filter + pump diagnostic (60-70% resolve at filter)</h3>
        <p>
          Most common Beko service call. Drain filter at bottom of tub is the first check — pull, clean,
          reinstall. If that doesn't resolve, drain pump impeller check, drain-hose routing, water-level
          sensor, control-board logic. Services range $89 diagnostic (filter clean only) to $180–$280
          (pump swap) to $340–$500 (control board).
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fail-block">
        <h3>Door latch failure on compact 18" chassis</h3>
        <p>
          Higher mechanical stress per cycle on the compact chassis produces plastic latch-hook wear at
          4-6 years. Replacement + realignment $180–$280. Often accompanied by gasket compression loss
          that disguises as a latch issue ($220–$340 gasket service when that's the actual fault).
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fail-block">
        <h3>Heating element failure — hard water scale</h3>
        <p>
          LA's hard water accelerates scale buildup on Beko heating elements. Element replacement
          $220–$360 when scale-compromised. Associated: DishSensor contamination (cleaning or
          replacement) $160–$240 when scale interferes with the auto-program water-quality sensor.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fail-block">
        <h3>Spray arm bearing + clogging</h3>
        <p>
          Upper and lower spray-arm bearings wear at 5-8 years; clogging from food debris + hard-water
          scale is ongoing preventive maintenance. Arm replacement $140–$240; clean + bearing service
          $120–$180 without parts swap.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fail-block">
        <h3>Circulation pump failure on 8-plus-year units</h3>
        <p>
          Long-service-life Beko units at 8-plus years occasionally see circulation pump failures —
          water not reaching spray arms even though fill cycle completes. Pump swap $380–$580. Distinct
          from drain-pump failure, which is a more common and lower-cost service.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="fail-block">
        <h3>Control board + DishSensor calibration</h3>
        <p>
          Main control board faults ($340–$500) are less common than mechanical-part failures on Beko
          but occur. DishSensor (Beko's water-turbidity auto-program sensor) calibration drift
          occasionally requires sensor replacement ($180–$280) when dishes come out under-washed
          despite the machine running full cycles.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

